{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477036","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477036"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:55:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:55:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14161"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14161","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14161"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.85,0.01,0.11,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6844"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55827"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6844","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6844"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14161"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41373"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1516"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15536"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55827","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55827"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA nine-month-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with his parents due to sudden onset of profuse vomiting and lethargy. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date. His parents report that the symptoms started about two hours after he was given cow\u0027s milk for the first time. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears pale and lethargic. His pulse rate is 160/min, blood pressure 80/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 40/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. His abdomen is soft and non-tender. There is no rash or swelling noted. Capillary refill time is 3 seconds.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sepsis","Food Protein-Induced Enterocolitis Syndrome (FPIES)","Viral gastroenteritis","Anaphylaxis","Intussusception"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation in this case is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003EFood Protein-Induced Enterocolitis Syndrome (FPIES)\u003C/strong\u003E. FPIES is a non-IgE mediated food allergy that typically presents in infants with profuse vomiting, lethargy, and sometimes diarrhoea, occurring 1-4 hours after ingestion of the trigger food. In this case, the symptoms began about two hours after the first exposure to cow\u0027s milk, which is a common trigger for FPIES.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnaphylaxis\u003C/strong\u003E is an IgE-mediated allergic reaction that typically occurs within minutes of exposure to the allergen. It usually presents with urticaria, angioedema, respiratory distress, and/or cardiovascular collapse. The absence of skin or respiratory symptoms, and the delayed onset of symptoms (2 hours) make anaphylaxis less likely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESepsis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with similar symptoms of lethargy and poor perfusion. However, the acute onset of symptoms shortly after food ingestion, and the absence of fever, make sepsis less likely. Sepsis would typically have a more gradual onset and would not be so closely tied to food ingestion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EViral gastroenteritis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause vomiting and lethargy in infants. However, the sudden onset of symptoms after ingestion of a new food, and the severity of the presentation, are more suggestive of FPIES than a viral illness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntussusception\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with intermittent severe abdominal pain, vomiting, and sometimes bloody stools. While it can cause lethargy, the absence of abdominal tenderness or a palpable mass, and the clear temporal relationship with food ingestion, make intussusception less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to diagnosing FPIES is recognizing the characteristic presentation of profuse vomiting and lethargy occurring 1-4 hours after ingestion of the trigger food, typically in infants. It\u0027s important to note that FPIES can sometimes be mistaken for sepsis or other acute illnesses due to its severe presentation. Management involves fluid resuscitation, avoidance of the trigger food, and in some cases, the use of ondansetron to control vomiting.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Food Protein-Induced Enterocolitis Syndrome (FPIES) typically presents with profuse vomiting and lethargy 1-4 hours after ingestion of the trigger food.","Food Protein-Induced Enterocolitis Syndrome is often misdiagnosed as sepsis or viral gastroenteritis due to its acute presentation.","Unlike IgE-mediated food allergies, Food Protein-Induced Enterocolitis Syndrome does not cause typical allergic symptoms such as urticaria or angioedema."],"references":["Calvani M, Anania C, Bianchi A, D\u0027Auria E, Cardinale F, Votto M, Martelli A, Tosca M, Chiappini E, Brambilla I, Miraglia Del Giudice M, Caffarelli C. Update on Food protein-induced enterocolitis syndrome (FPIES). Acta Biomed. 2021 Nov 29;92(S7):e2021518. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34842596/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41373"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14161"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41373"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-18T11:39:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-18T11:39:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6844"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55827"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"39","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/39"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immunology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attribut